'''Kambe Kōtachi Shinmei-sha''' (神戸神館神明社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Matsusaka City, Mie Prefecture, Japan. It is one of the claimants to the Engishiki-listed "Ohi Shrine" in Iitaka District, Ise Province, and is traditionally identified as a former Ise shrine site (Moto Ise) where Yamatohime-no-mikoto temporarily stayed at Iino-takamimiya while searching for the place to enshrine Amaterasu. Its former shrine rank was that of a village shrine.

==Shrine name==
Historically called "Kan-date Shrine", the Shrine Ledger of 1952 (Shōwa 27) notes that it was also called "Ohi Shrine". However, during the Meiji Restoration, the Engishiki-listed Ohi Shrine was identified with Goshirō Hachiman (now {{ill|Matsusaka Shrine|de|Schrein von Matsusaka|ja|松阪神社|zh|松阪神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsusaka Shrine|1=Matsusaka Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11532402}}) in the same city. Therefore, the Shrine Inspector designated the formal name as "Kambe Kōtachi Shinmei-sha". According to the Seya Rigon (勢陽俚諺), "Kan-date" was sometimes written as "Kōtatsu".

==Deities enshrined==
The following four kami are the primary enshrined deities:
* {{ill|Spirit of the Grand Shrine of Ise (Inner Shrine)|de|Geist des Ise-Schreins (Inneres Heiligtum)|ja|皇大神宮|zh|伊勢神宮内宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Spirit of the Grand Shrine of Ise (Inner Shrine)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Kōtai Jingū|qid=Q11581011}} (Amaterasu-ōmikami)
* {{ill|Spirit of the Grand Shrine of Ise (Outer Shrine)|de|Geist des Ise-Schreins (Äußeres Heiligtum)|ja|豊受大神宮|zh|伊勢神宮外宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Spirit of the Grand Shrine of Ise (Outer Shrine)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Toyōke Daijingū|qid=Q11633343}} (Toyouke-ōmikami)
* {{ill|Yamatohime-no-mikoto|en|Yamatohime-no-mikoto|qid=Q4388732|lt=Yamatohime-no-mikoto|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto}} (Yamatohime-no-mikoto)
* {{ill|Otokazuchi-no-mikoto|de|Otokazuchi-no-mikoto|ja|乙加豆知命|zh|乙加豆知命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otokazuchi-no-mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|qid=Q135579677|1=Otokazuchi-no-mikoto}} (Otokazuchi-no-mikoto, ancestor of the Iitaka county head)

On November 10, 1906 (Meiji 39), the following three kami were merged into this shrine; their origins are unclear:
* {{ill|Amatsuhikohikoho Ninigi-no-Mikoto|de|Amatsuhikohikoho Ninigi-no-Mikoto|ja|正勝吾勝勝速日天忍穂耳命|zh|正勝吾勝勝速日天忍穗耳命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amatsuhikohikoho Ninigi-no-Mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to アメノオシホミミ|1=Ame-no-oshihomimi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q462555}}
* {{ill|Ōyamatsumi|en|Ōyamatsumi|qid=Q386563|qid=Q386563|lt=Ōyamatsumi|1=Ōyamatsumi}}
* {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|de|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花開耶姫命|zh|木花開耶姫命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konohanasakuya-hime|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to コノハナノサクヤビメ}}

==History==
The area was established as the *kanda* and *kōbe* of Iitaka District, as recorded in Engishiki, with two *chō* of kanda and 36 households of *kanbe*. According to the Kōtaijingū Gishikichō, during the reign of Emperor Suinin, Yamatohime-no-mikoto brought Amaterasu to this region, where the local clan head Otokazuchi-no-mikoto presented kanda and kōbe lands and built the Iino-takamimiya. The Yamato-hime Chronicle similarly notes that in Suinin 22, Yamatohime-no-mikoto worshipped the Great Kami at Iino-takamimiya for four years, receiving these lands from Otokazuchi-no-mikoto (ancestor of the Wani clan). From then on, offerings were sent to Ise Grand Shrine. The 1906 Shrine Ledger states that a shrine hall was constructed at this site to store these offerings; the Kōbe Office was established to administer local affairs, and Shinmei-sha was enshrined, with the old Kōbe villagers repeatedly rebuilding the shrine. According to the 1952 Shrine Ledger, in 1382 (Kōwa 2), Kitabatake Akiyasu donated four *koku* of shrine lands, a grant upheld by the Kii Domain during the Edo period, but abolished after the Meiji Restoration. A pond on the grounds was once harvested for rushes used to make mats, annually dedicated to Ise Grand Shrine.

In the early Meiji period, it was renamed "Kambe Kōtachi Shinmei-sha" and ranked as a village shrine.

===Identification as an Engishiki shrine===
The earlier ledger records that it was called "Ohi Shrine". The first to identify it as the Engishiki-listed Ohi Shrine was Deguchi Nobumichi’s *Shinmyōchō Kōshō*, citing the "Shimohino Ogawa" river east of the shrine as the "Shimohino Ogawa" in Engishiki. Because "hino" and "hi" are phonetically similar, this was argued as evidence. Conversely, Imamori Kiyonao in the *Ise Shikinaisha Kenroku* argued that "Shimohino Ogawa" refers to the Atago River flowing west of Kaki-hana Village, not east, and that "Ohi" has no relation to Shimohino. He noted that shrine offices for each of the six districts of Ise Province used the name "Kan-date Shrine" to enshrine the spirit of Ise Grand Shrine, and since Otokazuchi-no-mikoto appears among the enshrined kami here, this shrine served as the guardian for Iitaka’s kōbe and should be identified as a Kokutsu Shrine. He accordingly identified the Engishiki Ohi Shrine with the current Matsusaka Shrine instead.

==Shrine buildings and subsidiary shrines==
The main hall is built in the Shinmei-zukuri style. Other structures include the worship hall and office. A _reisha_ shrine dedicated to the war dead from the Meiji Restoration through the Greater East Asia War is located on the grounds.

